        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The major purpose of this project is to detect dust continuum emission. We choose Band 6 because
at this frequency, dust emission is already much brighter than the potential free-free continuum
emission either from the shock-ionized thermal radio jets of the YSOs, or from the ionized
surface of YSOs due to external UV illumination. Based on experiences of SMA observations 
towards the nearby YSOs, we think on the 200-4000 AU spatial scales that we are probing,
observations at higher frequency bands will potentially be subject to the optically thick dust.
The proposed Band 6 observations also maintain a reasonably large field of view, which allows 
to mosaic efficiently. Observations at longer than 1 mm wavelengths (e.g. Band 3,4) are subject
to bright confusion from free-free emission. It is difficult for the current generation optical
and infrared telescopes to observe YSOs in this field, because of the confusion by the extremely
crowded stellar cluster and the dust obscuration.

The proposed correlator setup maximizes the continuum bandwidth. In addition, we will cover 
the HCN 3-2 and HCO+ 3-2 lines, as well as several hot core and disk tracers that we routinely
observe from Galactic star-forming regions including SO2 9(5,5)-10(4,6) and OCS 22-21 in 
baseband 3 and SO 5(6)-4(5) in baseband 1. We will also cover the shock tracer SiO 6-5 in
baseband 2. The observations of HCN, HCO+, and SiO will be combined with our ALMA cycle-2 1"
resolution observations of the same lines. We will try smoothing and tappering to yield the
optimized angular and velocity resolution as well as brightness sensitivity for each molecular
lines. Therefore, we will use FDM mode for this project. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The major purpose of this project is to detect young stellar objects at 200-4000 AU scales
(~0".03-0".5). We choose the C36-8 array configuration because it maximizes the sensitivity 
in these angular/spatial scales. In addition, the C36-8 array configuration is the most 
efficient to filter out the confusion from the more extended structures. 

This is a stand-alone experiment. However, we will also take the advantage of the existing 
1" resolution (including ACA and TP) data from our previous top 10% rated (fully observed) cycle-2 project 2013.1.00857.S (PI: Mills, E.A.C.), which have covered the entire CND with 
68 mosaic pointings of the 12m-array, at the same frequency bands. The uv-coverage of these
existing data is excellent for combining with the proposed cycle-3 obvservations, for 
recovering the short-spacing information. 

Therefore, we do not require cycle-3 observations in the more compact array 
configurations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Theoretical Noise Level:
We request to achieve a continuum rms noise level of 60 uJy/beam. Our 4-sigma continuum
sensitivity can detect dust emission from YSOs with mass as low as the low-mass YSO HL Tau
[M(gas+dust)~0.7 Msun]. The "OT Time Estimate" estimates the on-source time for each of the 
12 proposed target source fields to be ~5 minutes, and ~10-20 minutes for the field centering 
on Sgr A* (more in Justifications for User-Defined Calibration).

We will perform fast-switching in between the proposed 12 target source fields and Sgr A* 
in short duty-cycles. The requested on-source exposure time thus will be spread into a large 
hour angle range, will help achieve a higher image dynamic range. We notice that after changing
from the system-defined calibration to user-defined calibration, one hour of additional overhead
time has been automatically added to our project by OT before we include any additional
calibrators. We think the current overhead time can already take into account the impact of
observing efficiency by performing fast-switching.

Confusion of Extended Dust Emission:
On the proposed spatial scales (200~4000 AU), the density distribution function of the
interstellar medium (ISM) in the CND is largely unknown, and cannot be realistically modeled 
from simulation because of the lack of the observational constraints. Based on our existing 
dust continuum images with lower angular resolution, assuming the worst case scenario that 
there is no missing flux in the proposed observations, we estimate an upper limit of the 
median flux within the proposed maximum recoverable angular scale (~0".5) to be 0.52 mJy, 
which is merely 2 times higher than our requested 4-sigma detection limit of "flux per 
synthesize beam". In reality, the missing flux will push this extended confusion to be 
several times lower. On the spatial scales probed by the proposed observations, dust emission
from the extended ISM is likely much fainter than the YSOs that we are looking for. According 
to the technical handbook, we can achieve an image dynamic range of ~100 even without doing
fast-switching for phase referencing (see justifications for user-defined calibrations). 
Our targeted 0.7 Msun objects remain well above the confusion limit, and we think the requested
detection limit in this project is the most appropriate. This project will gauge the feasibility
of future observations to improve sensitvity for recovering the lower mass YSOs.

Confusion of Free-Free Emission Knots:
The proposed observations may be confused with free-free emission from ionized gas knots. The
recent 0".09x0".05 resolution JVLA observations at the 9 mm wavelength (34 GHz) covering the 
30" vicinity of Sgr A* detected 44 partially resolved compact sources (Yusef-Zadeh et al. 2015).
Only two of these sources show peak fluxes higher than the proposed 2-sigma of 120 uJy 
(126 uJy and 482 uJy), and the others are mostly several times dimmer. Assuming these ionized 
gas knots are optically thin in free-free emission thus have flat spectral slopes alpha~0, and
considering that the proposed targets fields are &gt;2 times further away from the ionizing source,
we think the targeted sensitivity limit in this ALMA cycle-3 project is in the regime well avoid
the free-free confusion. Nevertheless, we will retrieve archival VLA and JVLA data to constrain
the upper limits of the free-free emission fluxes for the identified YSO candidates.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The proposed observations will be combined with our previous top 10% rated (fully observed) 
cycle-2 project 2013.1.00857.S, which mosaic the entire CND with 1" resolution, including ACA 
and TP (PI: Mills, E.A.C.) This allows generating very high resolution images of the HCN 3-2, 
HCO+ 3-2, SiO 6-5 lines and various hot core and disk tracers. To preserve spectral line
information, we do not want to perform spectral averaging.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_HIGH_DATA_RATE</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The proposed observations have 12 target source fields; one gain-phase calibration field 
Sgr A* (~1 Jy), which is only ~1' from all 12 target source fields; and one 
gain-phase/amplitude calibration field J1733-130 (NRAO530).  

To achieve a high image dynamic range, we request performing fast-switching in between the
proposed 12 target sources fields and Sgr A*, for deriving accurate phase solutions. Since 
Sgr A* is time-variable, we will derive the gain amplitude solution by referencing every 5
minutes to J1733-130 which has been known to have a relatively stable absolute flux level. 
Sgr A* is a compact bright source, which will provide good gain phase solutions. 
In the case that we resolve extended structures immediately associated with Sgr A*, 
we will use J1733-130 scans to calibrate for an initial image of Sgr A*, and then use this
initial image model to bootstrap the gain phase solutions before implementing to the target
source fields. With this calibration scheme, the data will be useful even in the case that 
the WVR solutions are imperfect, and therefore should be one of the most doable Band 6 
mosaic with 10 km baselines.

An additional advantage provided by this calibration strategy is that we expect to achieve the
image dynamic range of from a few hundreds to over one thousand towards the gain-phase field 
Sgr A*. Since the 1 mm flux of Sgr A* is ~1 Jy, based on the expected dynamic range, we also
expect that we can detect massive YSOs with 1 mm fluxes around a few mJy within this gain-phase
field, which will reveal YSOs immediately around the supermassive black hole. The expected on
source time for Sgr A* is 10~20 minutes but with not very redundant uv-samplings, is deep
enough for this purpose. If we detect YSOs in this central field, we expect to be able to 
detect proper motions of these YSOs in cycle-4 or 5, depending on array configuration schedule.
Moreover, this calibration strategy will permit us to robustly subtract the sidelobe response 
from each field to Sgr A*, to suppress the confusion. 

The Sgr A* is a 1 Jy source at the proposed frequency. The antenna sidelobe response may 
confuse the our imaging. Our user-defined calibration strategy intends to permit modeling 
and subtracting this confusion to a level well below the confusion limit in the proposed 
12 target source fields. Considering the less than a few percents of antenna sidelobe response,
and considering the imaging dynamic range of several hundreds after self-calibration such 
that the modeling error of Sgr A* emission is &lt;&lt;1%, the sidelobe confusion in the proposed 
12 target source field is expected to be a few tens of micro-Jy, which will be below our
requested 4-sigma detection limit. We will also eliminate the effect of the variable source
Sgr A* in imaging for achieving a high dynamic range using the technique described by
our team members Zhao et al. (1991 Nature, 354, 46).

Our team members comprise experts in radio interferometry and high dynamic range imaging, 
e.g. Liu, Mills, Zhao, Matsushita, Wright, and Ho.</prj:justificationText>
