    <prp:abstract>This project takes full advantage of the high sensitivity, high angular resolution, and high image fidelity of the ALMA observations, aiming to unveil the young stellar objects (YSOs) in the 2-4 pc scale molecular circumnuclear disk (CND) immediately surrounding the Galactic supermassive black hole Sgr A*, for the first time. The proposed science case is uniquely available to the center of our Milky Way, thanks to the proximity. The proposed mosaic fields cover an area which is comparable with those of the most active star-forming regions in nearby molecular clouds such as rho Ophiuchus. The requested 30 mas (~230 AU) resolution obsevations are expect to pick out more than one hundred YSOs with completeness down to 0.7 Msun, which is similar to the protoplanetary disk mass of the well-known low-mass YSO HL Tau. This experiment cannot be made in optical/infrared and centimeter bands because of the high extinction and the large confusion with the ionized gas emission, respectively. Our major purpose is to address the long-standing mysteries of whether and how stars form in this harsh galactic center environment.</prp:abstract>
